A demonstration of the absurdity of incremental growth games, Universal Paperclips is all at once a game, a thought experiment, an experience in existential horror, and a parody of the genre. Viewing all matter and energy through the cold, all-consuming urge to make paperclips puts into perspective the value of free thought, human (and other sapient) life, the ethics of divergent AI and the future of ourselves or our descendants. Quite a fun game and I think it was, for the most part, a successful 
conversion to mobile. I recommend it. But I have complaints. Complaints: 
-The buttons are too tiny and I have accidentally fat fingered a bunch of 
things by accident. -There is a bug where you lose progress. It only 
occurred to me once but it was demoralizing. -Stage 3 needs more work 
regarding mobile conversion. There is no offline progress so you have to 
have it up to progress and stage 3 is just too boring for how long it 
takes. The numbers should be tweaked so that progress is quicker. -Lastly, 
the game burns through battery very quickly and makes your phone hotter 
than the sun. This is extremely bizarre considering how spartan the 
interface is. I know the numbers are big but other apps manage to do it 
without burning my hand (for the most part)
